From: post-bo-patch-prep
Subject: [PATCH 01/04] C-1: k=1 CARPET gate — confirm R5 is subsumed by existing filter

Per docs/audit/LOSS_FORENSICS_APR17.md §4.R5 and
docs/audit/COMPETITIVE_INTEL_APR17.md §5.C-1: "forbid k=1 CARPET unless
ALL alternatives evaluate below −1."

The existing T-20f filter in move_gen.ordered_moves is strictly tighter
than R5: it drops k=1 CARPET whenever ANY non-k=1 legal move exists,
which is a superset of the R5 condition. Therefore R5 is a no-op
against the current implementation.

This patch adds a docstring note documenting that decision so a future
reader does not reintroduce a weaker gate. No behaviour change.

---
 3600-agents/RattleBot/move_gen.py | 12 +++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/3600-agents/RattleBot/move_gen.py
+++ b/3600-agents/RattleBot/move_gen.py
@@ -10,10 +10,20 @@
 v1.1 invariant (D-011 item 2): with exclude_search=True (interior nodes),
 the returned list contains NO SEARCH moves.

-v0.2 T-20f (V01_LOSS_ANALYSIS bug 1): k=1 CARPET rolls are strictly
+v0.2 T-20f / v0.4 C-1 (V01_LOSS_ANALYSIS bug 1 + LOSS_FORENSICS_APR17
+§4.R5 + COMPETITIVE_INTEL_APR17 §5.C-1): k=1 CARPET rolls are strictly
 dominated (−1 point with no upside). We drop k=1 CARPET moves from the
 returned list UNLESS no non-k=1 legal move exists.

+C-1 / R5 audit note: the R5 proposal "forbid k=1 unless ALL alternatives
+evaluate below −1" is strictly subsumed by the `has_non_k1` gate below —
+whenever ANY non-k=1 legal move exists we already drop k=1, and
+therefore the `has_non_k1` case never leaves k=1 in the candidate list
+alongside another move that could score ≥ −1. Implementing R5 literally
+(requiring an eval pass inside move generation) would only re-enable
+k=1 in positions where we already suppress it. No code change; this is
+a no-op documentation patch.
